  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged from efforts to combat organized crime and drug trafficking\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States:\n- First comprehensive anti-money laundering legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and recordkeeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against Illicit Drug Trafficking\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Comprehensive Crime Control Act (1984)\n- US Patriot Act (2001) - expanded anti-money laundering provisions\n\n5. Global Expansion:\n- Increasing international cooperation\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Enhanced cross-border information sharing\n- Expanded regulatory frameworks\n\n6. Modern Approach:\n- Includes cryptocurrencies and digital transactions\n- More sophisticated tracking mechanisms\n- Increased international collaboration\n\nThese developments represent a progressive approach to controlling financial crimes.",
